<HL>
   First Capital
   Unit Blocked
   By Regulators
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/13/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP CCI FCH
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<NS>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
VIRGINIA (VA)
</RE>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California regulators clamped down on
operations at the largest insurance unit of First Capital
Holdings Corp., amid growing questions about the medium-sized
insurer's sudden plunge and the risk of major losses to
policyholders.
   The effects of the regulatory order rippled widely Friday,
in the latest woes to surface about a junk bond-laden
insurance company. Worries that regulators would dump the
company's junk bonds prompted a slump in the bond market,
which in turn triggered a wave of computer-guided stock sales
orders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s regulatory step, which had been anticipated,
echoed at <ORGANIZATION>American Express Co.</ORGANIZATION>, which said it will take a
<MONEY>$144 million</MONEY> pretax charge in the current quarter,
representing all of a <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT> stake in Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> held by <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc.</ORGANIZATION> unit. There were also negative implications for
<ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> unit, the leader of a <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY>
syndicated loan to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>.
   Beleagered <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> stock shed nearly a
third of its value in <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s tumbling stock markets,
falling <MONEY>43.75 cents</MONEY> to close at <MONEY>93.75 cents</MONEY> in composite
trading on the <ORGANIZATION>New York Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>
stock slid <MONEY>87.5 cents</MONEY> a share, to close at <MONEY>$23.875</MONEY> on the <ORGANIZATION>Big
Board</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Insurance Commissioner <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>, in a
cease and desist order, declared <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance
Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, to be in "hazardous"
financial condition and barred all policy redemptions and
loans. He also barred the company from writing any new
business. <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> will continue to pay ordinary
policyholder claims, including death and annuity benefits.
   The order, issued <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, was agreed to by
the company, which said the halt to redemptions would help
"stablilize" financial conditions at <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said his action was impelled by an
unexpected explosion in redemption demands from policyholders
after a disclosure of his demands that <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman</ORGANIZATION> bolster <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s financial base. From
an average of about <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> a day <DATE>two weeks ago</DATE>,
redemption requests surged to <MONEY>$25 million</MONEY> last <DATE>Monday</DATE>, <MONEY>$30
million</MONEY> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <MONEY>$60 million</MONEY> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, and <MONEY>$100
million</MONEY> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. Redemption requests that were in process
won't be paid as long as regulatory curtailments are in
effect.
   <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>, is one of two
major units of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>. It had assets of <MONEY>$4.46
billion</MONEY> at <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>, about 190,000 policyholders and 93,000
annuitants in 49 states. The other major unit, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, had
assets of <MONEY>$4.07 billion</MONEY> at <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>, with about 120,000
policyholders and 105,000 annuitants. In all, the two
companies have more than <MONEY>$31 billion</MONEY> of insurance liabilities
payable over many decades.
   A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Virginia's Bureau of Insurance</ORGANIZATION> said the
state agency is keeping a close watch on <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers</ORGANIZATION> and
is in contact with <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators. He said the company
currently is "in good standing" with regulators and meets
legal capital requirements.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, announcing the cease and desist order, said
that <PERSON>Gerry R. Ginsberg</PERSON>, president and chief operating officer
of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, was removed from oversight of the
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> unit and that <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>'s
president, <PERSON>Fred Arthur Buck</PERSON>, will report directly to <PERSON>Richard
K. DeScherer</PERSON>, acting chairman of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>.
   First Capital, with about <PERCENT>40%</PERCENT> of its investments in
high-yield investments, is the second major junk bond-laden
insurer to come under regulatory control in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> in the
past month. It's roughly half the size of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> unit, seized by
regulators on <DATE>April 11</DATE>. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said that <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s financial problems aren't as severe as those of
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s units.
   Although he asserted that <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> has serious
problems, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> announced a series of measures that
he said cure the company's woes, among them the sale of a
part of the company's business, a search for added capital,
and a program to sell the company's junk bonds -- which
sparked <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s swoon in the bond market. "We believe
policyholders will receive <PERCENT>100%</PERCENT> of contracted benefits," he
told reporters.
   But analysts were far less assured of a happy outcome and
speculated that there may be a "black hole," in the words of
one, of prospective losses. Among other things, the failure
of <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> to recapitalize the troubled
insurer concerned observers. Based on public numbers, such a
recapitalization would by one estimate require between <MONEY>$100
million</MONEY> and <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY> -- a relatively small sum for these
institutions, if it fixed the problem.
   "I have to wonder whether there's something that I just
don't know here and which the public hasn't been told," said
<PERSON>Ray Dirks</PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION>Baird, Patrick &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, who has in the
past recommended the stock of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>.
<ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> declined to comment on the
failure, to date, of their rescue talks with <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>.
   But a number of signs point to crumbling foundations at
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> and its units. Although the company
posted net income for <DATE>1990</DATE> of <MONEY>$7 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>15 cents</MONEY> a
share, on revenue of <MONEY>$980.7 million</MONEY>, its bond and real estate
investments showed marked weaknesses.
   A particular concern with analysts is the company's bond
portfolio, consisting not only of junk bonds, but in many
cases ones for which there is no active market. The so-called
"market value" of the insurer's bonds was about <MONEY>$700 million</MONEY>
less than the value at which they were carried on the
company's books at <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE> -- a gap almost twice the <MONEY>$383.8
million</MONEY> in shareholder equity at that date.
   However, only about <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> of the company's <MONEY>$7.48 billion</MONEY> in
short-term and long-term securities was valued by market
quotes. Market values for the rest were determined by various
"statistical services" and "internal methods," according to
the company's annual filing with the <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange
Commission</ORGANIZATION>.
   While the company's junk bond problems predominate, there
are other serious weaknesses. Some <PERCENT>12%</PERCENT> of the company's <MONEY>$275
million</MONEY> mortgage loan portfolio has interest more than 90
days overdue or is in foreclosure proceedings -- more than
twice the insurance industry average.
   <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>'s <MONEY>$144 million</MONEY> charge is likely to
produce a <DATE>second-quarter</DATE> loss at its <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION>
securities unit. And <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> may face additional
future costs from its association with <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>. About
three-quarters of the policies and annuities issued by <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance unit (formerly <ORGANIZATION>E.F. Hutton
Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>) are held by <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> customers -- a
potential legal liability if <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> fails.
   <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> has resisted <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s demands that
it inject capital into <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> but says it is
still "in discussions" with the commissioner.
   <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s problems also mean bad news for <ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION>,
which last year led the syndicate that lent <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY> to
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>. <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s cease and desist orders
block the flow of cash between <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> and its
parent. Some bankers have said that <ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> still holds most
of the <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY> loan because few other banks were willing
to buy portions of the debt. <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> declines to say how
much of the loan it still holds or whether it has reserved
against a potential loss on the loan.
   ---
   <PERSON>David B. Hilder</PERSON> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
