<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; INSURANCE; COMPANY; DEFECT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Shearson Lehman Brothers is negotiating with California insurance regulators,
trying to head off a potential failure of First Capital Life Insurance Co.,
which has more investments in "junk bonds" than other insurers still
operating, people who have been briefed on the talks said Sunday.;    Shearson
is the largest seller on Wall Street of First Capital's policies and owns 28
percent of the company, whose parent is based in Los Angeles.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SHEARSON OFFERS PLAN TO AVERT FAILURE OF
CALIFORNIA INSURER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     It is expected to offer two different approaches, either taking over
management of the insurer's portfolio, guaranteeing more than <MONEY>$2 billion</MONEY> that
backs the policies, or buying back all the universal life policies that
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> sold.;    That offer is expected to be discussed <DATE>today</DATE> when <PERSON>Howard
Clark Jr.</PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>, meets in <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> with
<PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s first elected insurance commissioner.;    A
spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> declined to comment <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. Calls to the <ORGANIZATION>California
Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> were not answered.;    <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>
has retained <ORGANIZATION>Salomon Brothers</ORGANIZATION> to examine ways to shore up its finances, which
were crippled with the collapse of the junk bond market last year.;   
Executives involved in the situation said <PERSON>Salomon</PERSON> was exploring at least two
options with <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>, including the sale of its universal life business
or the sale of a large number of the insurance company's junk bonds in the
open market.;    Both moves, if successful, would help <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s
troubled financial position.;    These executives said at least two potential
buyers for the universal life business had held discussions with <ORGANIZATION>Salomon</ORGANIZATION>,
although their names could not be immediately determined.;    A <ORGANIZATION>Salomon</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman did not return a telephone message Sunday.;    The scramble to deal
with <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> comes amid increasing concerns about the health of some
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> insurance companies.;    Last month, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators seized control
of <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>;   
Executive Life was then the insurance company with the largest portfolio of
junk bonds. <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>, who oversaw the seizure, said the company was in a
hazardous financial condition, primarily because of defaults and the declining
values in its junk bond portfolio.;    A recent accounting change also has
hurt <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>. As a result of the change, which affects how insurance
companies define junk bonds, <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>, which reported <DATE>last year</DATE> that <PERCENT>20.2
percent</PERCENT> of its assets were in junk bonds, has increased that figure to 40.7
percent.;    The negotiations between <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators are a
result largely of the Wall Street firm's ill-fated acquisition in <DATE>1988</DATE> of <ORGANIZATION>E.F.
Hutton &amp; Co</ORGANIZATION>. Hutton ran an insurance company, called <ORGANIZATION>E.F. Hutton Life</ORGANIZATION>, which
it sold in <DATE>1987</DATE> to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life.</ORGANIZATION>; 
  When <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> bought <PERSON>Hutton</PERSON>, it acquired a <PERCENT>44 percent</PERCENT> interest in <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, whose products the firm began to market.  </TEXT>
