<LP>
   California's insurance commissioner and American Express
Co. made little progress in their talks about a possible
rescue of First Capital Holdings Corp., amid signs that the
commissioner may soon take action against First Capital's
main unit.
   The commissioner, John Garamendi, met in New York
yesterday with Howard L. Clark Jr., chairman of American
Express's Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. securities unit.
According to people familiar with the talks, Mr. Garamendi
expressed reservations about plans proposed by Shearson that
would aid Shearson clients who bought policies from a unit of
First Capital, a Los Angeles-based insurance holding company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> is seeking a solution that would help all
policyholders of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>, which has been hurt by its
large investments in the high-risk, high-yield securities
called junk bonds. First Capital had <MONEY>$747 million</MONEY> in paper
losses on its <MONEY>$3.15 billion</MONEY> junk bond portfolio at year end
and <MONEY>$120 million</MONEY> of paper losses on other investments,
according to a filing with the <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange
Commission</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> had originally asked New York-based <ORGANIZATION>American
Express</ORGANIZATION> to put cash into <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>, but <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>
has rebuffed that suggestion, according to people familiar
with the talks.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> is also talking with officials of <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>,
whose main unit was the lead bank in a <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY> loan to
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> last year.
   First Capital, which is <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT> owned by <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>, has
about <MONEY>$8 billion</MONEY> in assets and is roughly half the size of
<LOCATION>Los Angeles-based</LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which last month
became the largest <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> insurance holding company to fail,
also because of losses on junk bonds. If regulators have to
take control of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s insurance units, one of
several possible actions, it will add significantly to a
burden of insurance insolvencies that is already the largest
in history.
   Although <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> is continuing to talk to both
<ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> about <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s problems,
he is concerned that publicity about <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s woes
could lead to an increase in requests from policyholders to
withdraw their funds, people familiar with the discussions
said.
   Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and New York-based <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>
declined to comment. A spokesman for <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> confirmed
that the commissioner met with <PERSON>Mr. Clark</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> but
declined to elaborate. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> said they
were aware of the meeting, which comes in the wake of
separate discussions between the commissioner and the company
over the infusion of more capital into the company's main
unit, <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance Co</ORGANIZATION>. They declined further
comment.
   <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> bought an insurance unit of the former <ORGANIZATION>E.F.
Hutton &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> shortly before <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> acquired <PERSON>Hutton</PERSON>. As a
result, many <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> customers hold policies issued by <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life Insurance</ORGANIZATION>.
   ---
   <PERSON>Rhonda L. Rundle</PERSON> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
