<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California regulators are looking into
whether two top officers of a now-failed First Capital
Holdings Corp. insurance unit improperly redeemed personal
insurance or annuity policies shortly before the unit was
seized by the state, a California insurance department
official said.
   The official, a spokesman for California Insurance
Commissioner John Garamendi, said the commissioner met
yesterday with Fred A. Buck, president of First Capital Life
Insurance Co. and with Julia S. Kelly, a senior vice
president, to discuss their actions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The two may have redeemed policies sometime before
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators seized <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, on <DATE>May 14</DATE>.
The commissioner and his officials are looking into whether
the company's officers improperly put themselves ahead of
other policyholders in making redemptions. It isn't clear
whether such actions would violate <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance law.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s spokesman declined to elaborate on either
the meeting or the investigation. <PERSON>Mr. Buck</PERSON> and <PERSON>Ms. Kelly</PERSON>
couldn't be reached.
   <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>, is a unit of Los
Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, which has said it plans
to file for Chapter 11 protection from creditors. <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>' other major insurance unit, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, was
seized by regulators in that state on <DATE>May 13</DATE>.
</TEXT>
