<DESCRIPT>  STOCK; INVESTMENT; COMPANY; CALIFORNIA; INSURANCE; REGULATION; MEETING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Negotiations between executives of Shearson Lehman and California insurance
regulators broke down Monday, as an effort to avert a potential failure of
First Capital Life Insurance Co. grew more intense, people who have been
briefed on the talks said.;    At the meeting Monday morning in Manhattan,
Shearson offered two proposals to improve the finances of the troubled
insurance company, which has more investments in "junk bonds" than other
insurers still operating.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  INSURER'S PLANS FOR BAILOUT REJECTED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Plans called insufficient;    But both proposals were rejected by <PERSON>John
Garamendi</PERSON>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner, as being insufficient to deal
with the company's deteriorating finances.;    <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>, which is the largest
seller of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s policies and owns <PERCENT>28 percent</PERCENT> of the company's
parent, offered proposals that would address the risks only to holders of
policies sold through the Wall Street firm.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> rejected those
proposals because he wanted a comprehensive solution to the company's
troubles, people who have been briefed on the discussions said.;    Rush to
find solution;    The breakdown in the talks set off a rush to find a solution
to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s situation, as <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> approached other financial
institutions for help. But people familiar with the situation said there was a
growing concern that anxieties in the marketplace might overtake the efforts,
resulting in a seizure of the insurance company.;    "The real problem now is
that there is real doubt about whether there is time remaining to work
anything out," one person familiar with the <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> situation said.
"Everybody is under pressure to come up with a solution before time runs
out.";    A spokesman for <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> confirmed talks with <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> executives
had been held <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>, but declined to elaborate. A spokesman for
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> declined to comment.;    <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> approached;    As the <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>
talks were hitting snags, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> was said to have approached executives at
<ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>, which was said to be a significant lender to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>,
the insurance company's parent.;    The hope, according to people who have
been briefed on those talks, is that <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> would infuse more capital into
the company to help preserve the quality of outstanding loans. A <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>
spokeswoman did not return a telephone call <DATE>Monday</DATE> night.;    At the same
time, <ORGANIZATION>Salomon Brothers</ORGANIZATION>, which has been hired by <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> to deal with its
unraveling finances, was said still to be exploring possible ways that the
insurance company could raise the badly needed cash. Those plans were said to
include selling off one of the company's businesses, or selling a large
portfolio of its junk bond holdings.;    The flurry of activity came in the
shadow of the recent seizure of <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which had been the insurance company with the largest
portfolio of junk bonds.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>, who oversaw the seizure, said at the
time that the company was in hazardous financial condition, primarily because
of defaults and declining values in that portfolio.;    The seizure of the
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> unit intensified concerns among regulators and the financial
community about the health of a number of other insurance companies, including
First Capital.;    An accounting change recently also hit <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s
capital base very hard. As a result of the change, <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>, which was
reporting last year that <PERCENT>20.2 percent</PERCENT> of its assets were in junk bonds, has
raised that figure to 40.7 percent.;    After the seizure of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>,
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> arranged two weeks ago to meet with <PERSON>Howard Clark Jr.</PERSON>, chairman and
chief executive of <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON>James D. Robinson III</PERSON>, chairman and chief
executive of <ORGANIZATION>American Express Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>'s parent. The recent negotiations
with the firm followed those meetings.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>'s concerns <DATE>Monday</DATE> were
said to have stemmed largely from what he saw as extensive problems at <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, at both its <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Capital</ORGANIZATION>, and its
<LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, which has <PERCENT>37.6
percent</PERCENT> of its assets in junk bonds, according to <ORGANIZATION>Weiss Research</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>West Palm
Beach</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>, firm. That is second only to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>California.</LOCATION>;    The
proposals rejected <DATE>Monday</DATE> by <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> involved <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>'s protection of its
customers who bought policies through the firm.;    Under the more radical
proposal, <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> would guarantee a portfolio of more than <MONEY>$2 billion</MONEY> that is
backing the policies and contracts of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> that are held by <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>
customers.;    Once the guarantee was made, the firm would begin a push to get
holders of the policies to cash them in, executives briefed on the talks said.
The portfolio contains investments in a range of securities, including a large
amount of the junk bonds that were purchased by <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>.  </TEXT>
