<LEADPARA>  A dispute between Shearson Lehman Brothers and California insurance regulators
intensified Tuesday, with the state's insurance commissioner contending that
the Wall Street firm had a responsibility to infuse First Capital Life
Insurance Co. with more capital.;    The struggling insurance company has more
investments in "junk bonds" than any other insurer still independently
operating.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GARAMENDI URGES SHEARSON TO SHORE UP AILING
FIRST CAPITAL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>, which owns <PERCENT>28 percent</PERCENT> of the insurer's parent, has been the
largest seller on Wall Street of the company's policies and contracts.;    The
dispute comes after more than two weeks of negotiations between the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
regulators and executives of <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> and its parent, <ORGANIZATION>American Express Co</ORGANIZATION>. On
<DATE>Monday</DATE>, those talks broke down when the regulators rejected proposals by
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> to protect its own customers who had purchased <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>
products. <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner, was said to be
seeking a more comprehensive solution to the problem.;    In statements
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said that the financial problems of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> appeared
to be extensive, and that both <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> needed to take
action to handle the entire problem, rather than protecting only their
customers.;    "Our continuing review" of the <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance
Company</ORGANIZATION> "indicates that the company needs a substantial infusion of cash,"
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said. "This is <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman</ORGANIZATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>'
responsibility.";    He added that the position in <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> had been
purchased "so that they would have annuities and life insurance products to
sell through their financial consultants, and sell they did.";    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>
said that from <DATE>1986</DATE> through the <DATE>first quarter of this year</DATE>, more than <PERCENT>75
percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s business was produced by <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION>American
Express</ORGANIZATION> employees.;    He said that, in that time, the two companies
"generated more than <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> worth of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> business. Meanwhile,
the percentage of non-investment grade assets of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> grew from less
than <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT> to more than <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> of total assets." A recent accounting
rule change was responsible for much of that change, increasing the junk bond
holdings <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> reported from <PERCENT>20.2 percent</PERCENT> of its assets to 40.7
percent.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said he believed that both <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>American
Express</ORGANIZATION> should make sure that <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> was viable, and referred to
<ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION>'s well-known advertising campaign.;    "If membership has its
privileges, than ownership has its responsibilities," he said.  </TEXT>
