<HL>
   California to Ban Accounting Practice
   It Says Inflates Insurers' Capital Levels
   ----
   By Susan Pulliam
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP FCH FEXC
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<NS>
BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
</RE>
<LP>
   California is forcing life insurers in the state to end an
accounting practice that regulators contend artificially
inflates an insurer's capital levels.
   As a result, the new rule will sharply reduce the reported
capital levels of many insurers operating in California. The
change, which hasn't been publicly announced, is the latest
attempt by California regulators to tighten control over
insurers following recent problems involving First Executive
Corp. and First Capital Holdings Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new rule, outlined in an <DATE>April 15</DATE> letter from <PERSON>John
Garamendi</PERSON>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance commissioner, to 640
insurance companies licensed to operate in the state, would
ban the use of a controversial reinsurance contract.
Reinsurance companies assume some of the risk on insurer's
policies in return for fees or a share in future revenue.
They also pay commissions for taking the policies, which
insurers list as capital. <PERSON>Norris Clark</PERSON>, chief of financial
analysis, says the department acted after it concluded that
companies had used questionable reinsurance agreements to
boost their capital levels.
   The rule, which takes effect at the end of this year, will
hit California-based companies hardest, but it also could
have an impact on reinsurers and any insurance company
operating in the state. "There are a lot of these
transactions out there," said <PERSON>Mr. Clark</PERSON>. "The early
indications are that it impacts a number of companies. There
are also insurers that have made their business out of
writing these agreements," he said.
   Of the life insurance companies operating in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>,
58 are based in the state. Companies that are based in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> would have to eliminate the transactions by <DATE>Dec.
31</DATE>, which would reduce their capital levels. Out-of-state
companies would have to choose between doing business in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and reducing their capital levels for reporting
purposes in the state.
   The accounting change helps explain some of the actions
taken recently regarding the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance unit of
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>
unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>. Regulators seized the unit of
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> after huge junk bond losses. <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
regulators are expected to sharply restrict the operations of
the <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> unit in a matter of days.
   People close to the situation say regulators made the
accounting change after examiners discovered several weeks
ago that <MONEY>$64 million</MONEY> of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance</ORGANIZATION>'s <MONEY>$107
million</MONEY> in capital at year end came from questionable
reinsurance agreements. Roughly <MONEY>$165 million</MONEY> of the <MONEY>$474
million</MONEY> in capital at <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> unit came
from these transactions, according to people familiar with
the company.
   Insurance companies routinely use reinsurance agreements
to lower their risk of doing business. Many kinds of
reinsurance also have the benefit of boosting capital,
because insurers are able to shift the expense of doing
business to the reinsurer. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> objects to
reinsurance agreements that serve only to raise an insurer's
capital, without also lowering the risk.
   The department has sent a survey to all 640 companies to
find out how widespread such practices are, <PERSON>Mr. Clark</PERSON> said.
   In the industry, the move "is creating chaos . . .," says
<PERSON>Bruce Winterhof</PERSON>, consulting actuary with <ORGANIZATION>Milliman &amp;
Robertson</ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide actuarial consulting firm. "There are
many insurance companies whose capital would be reduced under
the rule," he says.
</TEXT>
