<LP>
   Virginia regulators seized Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance
Co., the second major unit of beleaguered First Capital
Holdings Corp. to be curbed by regulators in less than a
week.
   The action by Virginia's Bureau of Insurance blocks all
policy redemptions and loans but permits routine payments of
death and annuity benefits, as well as accident and health
claims.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, had assets of
about <MONEY>$4.07 billion</MONEY> at <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>, and about 213,000 life
insurance policies and 97,000 annuitants.
   The unit is slightly smaller than <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life
Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>, whose business was sharply
curbed by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators on <DATE>Friday</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>
had assets of <MONEY>$4.46 billion</MONEY> at <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>, about 190,000
policyholders and 93,000 annuitants. Both companies have
substantial holdings of junk bonds.
   <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>'s move puts substantially all of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital
Holdings</ORGANIZATION>' insurance business under regulatory restrictions.
Together, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers and First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, have more
than <MONEY>$31 billion</MONEY> in life insurance benefits owed to
policyholders over the coming decades.
   Although industry watchers had expected <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>
regulators to swiftly follow <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s action, a <ORGANIZATION>Virginia
Bureau of Insurance</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said <DATE>Friday</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers</ORGANIZATION> was in "good standing" and that the company met
minimum capital requirements. The spokesman, <PERSON>Kenneth Schrad</PERSON>,
said he didn't know what had occurred between <DATE>Friday</DATE> and
yesterday to change the <ORGANIZATION>Bureau</ORGANIZATION>'s view.
   <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers</ORGANIZATION> said it was cooperating with <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>
regulators, adding that it believed the step was in the best
interest of policyholders.
   Much of the business of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers</ORGANIZATION> was written through securities dealers, who were
major sellers of annuities written by both companies, opening
the potential for substantial legal liability at various
brokerage companies.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION> securities unit of <ORGANIZATION>American
Express Co.</ORGANIZATION>, with a <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT> stake in <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>,
based in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, sold business that brought in some
<MONEY>$1.74 billion</MONEY> of premiums in the <DATE>last three years</DATE> at the two
companies, according to a <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange Commission</ORGANIZATION>
filing. <ORGANIZATION>PaineWebber Inc.</ORGANIZATION> accounted for business that brought
in <MONEY>$641.9 million</MONEY> over the same period.
   <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman</ORGANIZATION> have said they are
continuing talks with <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance regulators. As
previously reported, <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> said it will take a
<MONEY>$144 million</MONEY> pretax charge in the current quarter,
representing the <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT> stake. Also there are negative
implications for <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> unit, leader of a <MONEY>$275
million</MONEY> syndicated loan to <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>. A
<ORGANIZATION>PaineWebber</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman declined to comment on the company's
sales -- believed to have been written largely with <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers</ORGANIZATION>.
   Separately, <ORGANIZATION>Moody's Investors Service Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp.</ORGANIZATION> said they downgraded <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s subordinated debt.
</TEXT>
