<LEADPARA>  California State Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi Tuesday seized ailing
First Capital Life Insurance Co. of San Diego, after major lenders sought to
force its parent company into Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings.;    Garamendi
said that the state placed the company in conservatorship to protect the
interest of more than 250,000 First Capital policy and annuity holders. It is
the second largest failure of a life insurer ever, and comes on the heels of
the seizure last month of the biggest, Executive Life Insurance Co.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REGULATORS TAKE OVER AILING FIRST CAPITAL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  (box) Bidding opens on failed Executive Life, Page 6F.
Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The state took control of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> after a group of lenders headed by
<ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> petitioned late <DATE>Monday</DATE> to force its parent, <LOCATION>Los Angeles-based</LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Holdings Corp.</ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy for defaulting on a <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY> loan.;
   By placing <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> into conservatorship, regulators actively run the
company. <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> will still pay customers death and annuity benefits in
full, along with accident and health claims. But the state is prohibiting
policy redemptions and loans on policies.;    The effect of <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>'s action
is to shield the insurance company against claims filed by banks and other
creditors. "We place the insurance company in a protective envelope, if you
will, walling it off from all of its other creditors," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> told a state
Capitol news conference.;    <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> was a high-flying
insurance operation headed until <DATE>March</DATE> by <PERSON>Robert Weingarten</PERSON>, one of the
industry's highest-paid executives who last year took home <MONEY>$1.35 million</MONEY>. The
company's problems stem largely from investments in risky, high-yield junk
bonds.;    <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman</ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, owns <PERCENT>28 percent</PERCENT> of
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> and regulators have been pressuring the brokerage firm to
provide more financial support to the insurance units. Negotiations are
continuing on that issue.;    Last week, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> slapped restrictions on
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> after customers flooded the company with requests to cash
in their policies -- a situation analogous to a run on a bank. On <DATE>Monday</DATE>,
<LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> insurance authorities seized its sister unit, <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers Life
Insurance</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, Va.-based insurance firm slightly smaller than <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life.;    First Capital</ORGANIZATION> has assets of <MONEY>$4.46 billion</MONEY>, 190,000 life
insurance policyholders and 62,000 annuitants, the state said. <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers</ORGANIZATION> has assets of <MONEY>$4.07 billion</MONEY>, 120,000 policyholders and 105,000
annuitants. Both operate in 49 states.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> previously said that he
believes <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> policyholders will receive all of their benefits. At
the news conference, he said that he would not have placed the firm into
conservatorship had the creditors not sought to force it into bankruptcy. He
added that a liquidation of the company is not planned.; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED;
Policyholders can call the state <ORGANIZATION>Department of Insurance</ORGANIZATION> consumer hot line for
information -- (800) 927-HELP.  </TEXT>
