<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California insurance commissioner John
Garamendi, seeking to calm skittish bond markets, promised to
avoid "a fire sale" of billions of dollars of junk bonds from
two failed companies now in his department's control.
   "It isn't in anybody's interest to force this market down
by a disorderly liquidation process" of bonds held by
Executive Life Insurance Co. and First Capital Life Insurance
Co., Mr. Garamendi said at a public meeting Friday attended
by about 500 Executive Life policyholders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The commissioner, who took office in <DATE>January</DATE> and who has
blamed the failure of the two companies on his predecessor,
was greeted with applause and occasional levity during his
one-hour question-and-answer session.
   Junk bond markets sagged early last week after <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> seized <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION> and announced that his
officials planned to pare the company's big junk-bond
portfolio. Spooked, some holders of junk bonds began dumping
the securities. Executive Life is a unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> is a unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings
Corp</ORGANIZATION>. Both parent companies are based in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> and,
combined with other insurance units under state control in
<LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, hold more than <MONEY>$10 billion</MONEY> face value
of junk bonds.
   Most junk bonds fell 1/2 point <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s problems with jumpy bond markets are but
one of the many complications of a proposed restructuring of
about <MONEY>$10.17 billion</MONEY> in Executive Life assets. The <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
insurance department has said it will conduct what amounts to
an auction for groups interested in acquiring the failed
company's business.
   The front runner in that auction is a group lead by <ORGANIZATION>Altus
Finance</ORGANIZATION>, a <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT>-owned subsidiary of the French bank <ORGANIZATION>Credit
Lyonnais</ORGANIZATION>, which has committed to provide financing or a
letter of credit for as much as <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> in an as-yet
undetermined restructuring. The <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION> group has been
talking with <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> officials for some months and has
been analyzing a variety of complicated information that
other prospective bidders are only now going to be able to
review.
   Although little has been said publicly about the
prospective look of a "renewed" Executive Life company,
people familiar with the situation say that any restructuring
would consist of a successor company holding the liabilities
to current policyholders, backed by large portions of
Executive Life's present assets and an infusion of new
capital to shore up the company's depleted equity.
   While the assets of the company will need to be shored up,
its liabilities -- what it must pay to policyholders -- must
be reduced. It's expected that, at minimum, interest rates
paid to policy and annuity holders on cash balances will be
sharply reduced.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE> that he won't require bidders
for Executive Life to sell the company's deeply devalued
holdings of junk bonds, but rather to issue guaranties of a
minimum value for the portfolio. Such a guarantee would
likely be backed by an outside bank or by assets held by the
bidders. He added that his officials were looking for ways in
which policyholders might participate in gains in bond values
in future years.
   However, it's likely that any renewed Executive Life would
have to prune its bulging portfolio of high-yield bonds.
Insurance analysts doubt that policyholders would trust a
company with large holdings of high-yield securities. Also,
state restrictions are expected that will limit junk-bond
holdings to no more than <PERCENT>20%</PERCENT> of assetsfar below the more than
<PERCENT>60%</PERCENT> held by Executive Life. <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> already has a <PERCENT>20%</PERCENT> limit.
   Despite the complications of auctioning Executive Life,
<PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> told the policyholders <DATE>Friday</DATE> that it's far
better than the alternative. "Liquidation," he said, "would
be an unmitigated disaster for everybody involved; it would
take forever to liquidate this company {because} there is no
ready market for many of the assets."
</TEXT>
