<DESCRIPT>  INSURANCE; COMPANY; BANKRUPT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  First Capital Holding Corp., reeling after a $770 million first-quarter loss
and the seizure of its two primary insurance units, is headed for bankruptcy
court, published reports said today.;    First Capital, which reported the
huge loss Monday, plans to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from its
creditors, the Los Angeles Times and The Wall Street Journal reported.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FIRST CAPITAL REPORTED NEAR CHAPTER 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Charles Perkins</PERSON> declined to say when the company
would file, noting the firm still has some assets, including an insurance
company in Britian.;    In its earnings report, <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> reported a loss
from continuing operations of <MONEY>$2.3 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>5 cents</MONEY> a share, in the first
quarter.;    The rest of the <MONEY>$770 million</MONEY> loss was the result of the firm's
writing off of the net assets of its two insurance subsidiaries, which were
seized by regulators in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and Virginia.;    The first quarter losses
from San Diego-based <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, Va.-based
<ORGANIZATION>Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> amounted to <MONEY>$768 million</MONEY> or <MONEY>$16.44</MONEY> per
share.;    The company earned <MONEY>$16.1 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>35 cents</MONEY> a share, for the
quarter ending <DATE>March 31, 1990.</DATE>;    <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators seized <ORGANIZATION>First Capital
Life</ORGANIZATION> in an effort to prevent the parent company's creditors -- including
<ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> -- from forcing it into bankruptcy. <ORGANIZATION>Citibank</ORGANIZATION> leads a consortium that
loaned <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$275 million</MONEY> last year.;    Insurance Commissioner <PERSON>John
Garamendi</PERSON> said he took the steps to protect <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> policy holders.;   
If the holding company files for bankruptcy protection, "it would not affect
the assets of the insurance company," said <PERSON>Tom Epstein</PERSON>, deputy <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
insurance commissioner.;    The company "is a protective wall and insurance
policy holders would suffer no adverse impact," he said.;    The insurers were
awash in junk bond investments, whose value plunged in recent years.;   
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said recently that policy holders and annuitants with companies held
by <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> were likely to receive <MONEY>100 cents</MONEY> on the dollar on their
policies and investments.  </TEXT>
