<DESCRIPT>  INSURANCE; COMPANY; BAN; STATE; REGULATION; ORGANIZATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  State regulators Friday ordered a $4.5 billion insurance company to stop
writing new policies, saying its overdose on junk bonds has nearly killed it.;
   State Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi's action means San Diego-based
First Capital Insurance Co. will no longer honor requests from customers who
have rushed to cash in $265 million worth of policies.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STRICT RULES ON FIRST CAPITAL
INSURER ORDERED TO STOP WRITING NEW LIFE
POLICIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "The action I have taken is intended to stabilize and begin the process of
rehabilitating the company," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> told a capitol news conference. "It
will give us the necessary time to develop a long-term strategy to return the
company to financial health.";    190,000 policies nationwide;  First Capital
Life, whose most prominent stockholder is <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION>, has issued
190,000 life insurance policies nationwide.;    But <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said junk bonds
grew from <PERCENT>16 percent</PERCENT> of its investment portfolio in <DATE>1986</DATE> to <PERCENT>46 percent</PERCENT> in
<DATE>1991</DATE>, and it had operating expenses roughly twice the industry's average.;   
"First Capital Life's problems are serious and require immediate attention,"
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;    The state's intervention, which comes about a month after
state regulators seized major portions of junk bond-dependent insurer <ORGANIZATION>First
Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, means <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> cannot make payments to its parent
company or its affiliates without state approval.;    'The time we need';  The
company issued a three-paragraph statement <DATE>Friday</DATE> in which it said the state's
action will give it "the time we need to stabilize the company's finances and
assure long-term value of our customers' policies.";    "While we regret the
company has reached this point; we believe it was in the best interest of our
policyholders to take this step.";    As news of the company's shaky financial
status spread in recent weeks, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said, requests to cash in policies
grew from <MONEY>$25 million</MONEY> worth of surrenders on <DATE>Monday</DATE> to <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> worth
Thursday.;    "That type of increase and amount is an impossible situation for
the company," the insurance commissioner said.;    The state's first elected
insurance chief, noting that the brokerage <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION> owns <PERCENT>28
percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s stock and sold <PERCENT>75 percent</PERCENT> of its life insurance
policies from <DATE>1986</DATE> to this year, called on <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> to shore up the firm.;   
'Ownership has its responsibilities';  "We would expect that <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman</ORGANIZATION>
will accept the reality that ownership has its responsibilities," said
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>, employing a twist on the slogan of <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>'s parent, <ORGANIZATION>American
Express</ORGANIZATION>: "Membership has its privileges.";    The state's action does not
preclude <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> from honoring other insurance obligations such as death
benefits and annuities.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said "untimely stories in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
newspapers" that state regulators were negotiating with <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> to
assist <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> hastened the run by policyholders to cash in.;    "We
believe that in general the life insurance industry is a healthy industry,"
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said when asked if further failures are likely. "It is not in
similar circumstances as the savings and loan industry. It's an industry that
has a very high percentage of the companies operating in a sound and wise
financial manner.";     TROUBLE AT FIRST CAPITAL; After reports of <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>'s financial plight set off a run of customers
trying to cash in their policies, the <ORGANIZATION>California Department of Insurance</ORGANIZATION>
stepped in <DATE>Friday</DATE> to keep the company afloat.; What's wrong with firm;
(box)<PERCENT>Forty-six percent</PERCENT> of its investments are in non-investment grade
securities -- 'junk bonds,' according to state Insurance Commissioner <PERSON>John
Garamendi.</PERSON>; (box)Operating costs -- twice the industry average -- were
elevated by "unusually high" fees charged by its parent, <ORGANIZATION>First Capital
Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, for asset management and other services, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;
(box)Reports that the firm was in trouble set off a groundswell of requests to
redeem policies -- <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> a day last week, <MONEY>$25 million</MONEY>, <DATE>Monday</DATE>, <MONEY>$30
million</MONEY>, <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <MONEY>$60 million</MONEY>, <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY>, <LOCATION>Thursday.</LOCATION>; What
state ordered firm to do; (box)Stop issuing new policies.; (box)Stop making
loans secured by policies; (box)Stop making payments to its parent company or
its affiliates without permission from state regulators.; <ORGANIZATION>State</ORGANIZATION>'s long-term
plan for firm; (box)Sell the company's universal life insurance business,
which has about <MONEY>$1.3 billion</MONEY> in assets.; (box)Reduce junk bond holdings to
less than <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> of its portfolio.; (box)Reduce operating costs.; (box)Get
cash infusion from <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and its brokerage <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman
Brothers</ORGANIZATION>, which own <PERCENT>28 percent</PERCENT> of the parent company.; If you have a policy;
(box)The state's action does not preclude payment of death benefits and
annuities.; (box)Policyholders can call the state <ORGANIZATION>Department of Insurance</ORGANIZATION>
consumer hot line for information -- (800) 927-HELP.; <ORGANIZATION>Mercury News</ORGANIZATION>  </TEXT>
