<LP>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Barely five months into the job,
California's first elected insurance commissioner, John
Garamendi, says he doesn't like the work.
   "It sure hasn't been fun," he told a group of insurance
underwriters recently. "I had no idea that the events and the
task would be so difficult."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Elected with a mandate to roll back auto insurance rates,
<PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, 46 years old, has instead become the warden of
the biggest insurance failures ever. Between them, <ORGANIZATION>Executive
Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> owe
more than <MONEY>$14 billion</MONEY> to holders of policies and annuities.
The shortfall in assets has yet to be determined.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s actions will mean a lot -- not only to
more than half a million policyholders across the nation but
to a life insurance industry undercut by public doubt. Should
he succeed in rehabilitating the failed companies and cutting
auto rates, industry experts say, the darkly handsome and
ambitious <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> will have transformed the obscure
post of state insurance commissioner into a seat of power and
a locus of political change.
   The size of the financial failures, the commissioner's
political skills and <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s frequent role as a cradle
of political trends already have brought public recognition
and a potentially pivotal role in an emerging debate over the
direction of insurance regulation. "<PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> could
become the prototype for more active insurance commissioners
around the country," says <PERSON>William O'Neill</PERSON>, vice president for
insurance rating services at <ORGANIZATION>Standard &amp; Poor's Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   In an unusual step, the commissioner will meet today with
hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Executive Life policyholders
at a public gathering in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>. Few if any of his
fellow regulators would attend such a meeting "unless they
were dragged there," says <PERSON>James Long</PERSON>, insurance commissioner
of <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION>National Association
of Insurance Commissioners</ORGANIZATION>, the overseer of the nation's
system of state regulation.
   For the moment, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> has been able to blame the
downfall of Executive Life and of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> on his
predecessor, <PERSON>Roxani Gillespie</PERSON>, whose supervision he calls a
case of "Don't worry-be happy." <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> promises a
return of "the hard hand of regulation" to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>'s largest
insurance market. <PERSON>Ms. Gillespie</PERSON> -- who like previous
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance commissioners and the top regulators in
38 other states was appointed by the governor -- defends her
actions as appropriate.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> came to office in <DATE>January</DATE> under the terms of
Proposition 103, a <DATE>November 1988</DATE> referendum that created the
elected commissionership and mandated sharply lower auto
insurance rates. The rates provision is forcefully opposed by
what the commissioner calls a "gang of 84" insurance
companies, which have taken the matter to court.
   By most standards, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, a former state
legislator, college football hero and wrestler, is an oddity
in the world of insurance regulation. He is a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard
Business School</ORGANIZATION> graduate who grew up in a well-heeled family
on a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> ranch and now owns a pear orchard in <LOCATION>Walnut
Grove</LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION>. He has a populist style, is
comfortable with TV cameras and has a talent for catchy
phrases.
   When <PERSON>Ms. Gillespie</PERSON> approved a rash of rate increases only
days before she left office, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> blasted it as a
"Christmas present to the fat-cat insurance companies." And
when <ORGANIZATION>American Express Co.</ORGANIZATION>, with a <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT> stake in the parent of
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, resisted <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s private requests
that it add cash to the beleaguered company, he publicly
charged <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> and its <ORGANIZATION>Shearson Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION>
investment unit with unseemly abandonment. "If membership has
its privileges, then ownership has its responsibilities," he
declared. <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> has said it will take appropriate
actions but hasn't accepted any obligation to recapitalize
the ailing company.
   His willingness to shoot from the lip has raised eyebrows
in the insurance business, where many worry that <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON>'s stewardship of Executive Life, a <LOCATION>Los
Angeles-based</LOCATION> unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, and of <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, a San Diego-based unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital
Holdings Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, could be marred by rash actions. There also
is concern that the commissioner has created an unrealistic
wave of hope with his plans to resuscitate what appear to be
badly damaged companies.
   There has been one major slip. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> announced his
conservatorship of Executive Life in optimistic tones, saying
that policy redemptions and loans would be blocked but that
routine death-benefit and annuity checks would continue at
<MONEY>100 cents</MONEY> on the dollar. But for nearly two weeks, claimants
were left hanging by a glitch in an <ORGANIZATION>Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION>
order. While death benefits are now being paid at <MONEY>100 cents</MONEY>
on the dollar, annuity payments are being made at <MONEY>70 cents</MONEY>.
The misstep irked regulators in many states.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> has been guarded about a point of vital
interest to state regulators: the debate over what role, if
any, the federal government should play in the patchwork of
state insurance regulation. Though some industry and
regulatory people say the commissioner of the nation's most
populous state might break ranks and support federal
oversight, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> says he wants to give state
regulation more time. But he suggests that more large
failures would change his mind. "The schedule is driven by
events," he says.
   Many who know him say <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> himself is driven. For
more than 15 years he was a state legislator, concentrating
on ecological and economic issues. "He was never a superstar
in the state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> but was always extremely ambitious," says
<PERSON>Dick Rosengarten</PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION>Calfornia Political Week</ORGANIZATION>, a
newsletter.
   In <DATE>1982</DATE>, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, then 37, ran in the Democratic
primary for governor and lost. Soon afterward, he tried to
unseat the president pro tem of the state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. "It was the
shortest-lived coup in history -- less than 36 hours," <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> says of his defeat. He also lost a bid for the
nomination for state controller.
   But as commissioner, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> has found the high
profile he has sought.
   "At the moment he's the most visible politician in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>," says <PERSON>Clinton Reilly</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> political
consultant who has advised <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
