<LP>
   Creditors of First Capital Holdings Corp., Los Angeles,
which filed for bankruptcy protection last summer, said they
plan to ask the court overseeing the proceedings for
permission to file suit against Shearson Lehman Brothers, a
unit of American Express Co.
   The creditors said they are taking the action because they
don't believe they will receive a favorable settlement in the
bankruptcy proceedings. The expected filing in the Los
Angeles court today would follow two similar suits by
investors who charged that Shearson misled them about the
holding company's problems.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> is the holding company of <ORGANIZATION>Fidelity
Bankers Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>. Shearson owns <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT>
of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>.
   The lawsuit is said to charge <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> and some directors
and officers of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION> with mismanagement of
the company and a breach of their duties to the company.
Shearson is also charged with not taking action to prevent
the failure of the company even though <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> was aware of
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital Holdings</ORGANIZATION>' problems.
   Prior to the seizure of the two life insurance units last
<DATE>summer</DATE>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner, <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>,
asked <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> to inject additional capital into the
companies. When <ORGANIZATION>American Express</ORGANIZATION> failed to put up additional
funds, he took over the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> unit. That move was
followed by a takeover of the <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> company by regulators
there.
</TEXT>
