<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California regulators unveiled an
intricate, two-part plan to restructure Executive Life
Insurance Co. that would offer difficult choices to
policyholders and clearly signaled for the first time that
they and other creditors could suffer substantial initial
losses.
   The proposed resolution of the nation's largest insurance
failure -- termed a "rehabilitation blueprint" by California
Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi -- is only a suggested
structure for prospective bidders for the insolvent insurer,
a unit of Los Angeles-based First Executive Corp. until it
was seized April 11 by state insurance regulators.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It isn't clear what the complicated blueprint could
produce for the nearly 170,000 life insurance policyholders,
75,000 individual annuitants and members of retirement and
other plans covered by 307 guaranteed investment contracts.
The results will depend in large part on the bids offered by
investor groups. But, by one estimate, holders who choose to
keep their policies with a successor company to Executive
Life might initially have policies worth <PERCENT>70%</PERCENT> or so of the
value assigned them by Executive Life. More could be
recovered over time, depending on a recovery in the junk bond
market and final recovery from state guarantee funds and
legal settlements.
   Holders of certain municipal securities backed by
Executive Life are likely to get <MONEY>30 cents</MONEY> or less on the
dollar under the plan, the insurance department said.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, who has promised maximum recoveries for
policyholders and annuitants, warned that his proposal is
dependent on a reversal of a <MONEY>$643 million</MONEY> claim by the
<ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION> for back taxes. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>,
together with his <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> counterpart, <PERSON>Salvatore Curiale</PERSON>,
will appear today before a congressional committee looking
into the Executive Life collapse.
   The plan announced yesterday makes no provision for a
second <ORGANIZATION>First Executive unit-Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> of
<LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, which was seized by regulators in that state.
Regulators have in the past suggested that a resolution might
be cast for the two companies, whose combined assets before
their failure totaled more than <MONEY>$13 billion</MONEY>.
   Under the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> plan, two entities would replace
Executive Life. The first, a successor company, would take
title to most of the former insurance company's assets and
all its liabilities. A second entity, a liquidating trust,
would be established to recoup money from state insurance
guarantee funds around the country, from litigation and from
various Executive Life investment assets that are considered
high-risk securities.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> signaled that bidders for Executive Life's
business will be expected to inject at least <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> to
<MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> in cash in the successor company to recapitalize
it. And billions of dollars of guarantees will be required to
shore up Executive Life's junk bond-laden portfolio. <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> has said he prefers the guarantee approach -- in
which buyers would promise to put in extra money if the bonds
fall below a certain level -- to a "fire sale" that would
depress junk bond markets.
   The <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> commissioner left open the required amount
of guarantees. However, <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION>, a <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT>-owned subsidiary
of the French bank <ORGANIZATION>Credit Lyonnais</ORGANIZATION>, is leading an investor
group that has said it will put up <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> or more in cash
and guarantees.
   People familiar with the bidding process say there are
three other interested parties in addition to <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION>,
which is the only publicly declared bidder. Under the bidding
process, qualified interested parties will have several weeks
to inspect internal Executive Life accounts and then to file
a bid. Any settlement will eventually have to be approved by
a state court in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> that is overseeing the
conservatorship process.
   Policy and annuity holders will face some particularly
hard choices if the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> plan proceeds. At the creation
of the successor company, they will have the option of
cashing out their policies at amounts that may be much less
than <MONEY>50 cents</MONEY> on the dollar. Or, they may agree to turn over
their policies to the successor company, where they would be
locked in for a minimum period -- probably three to five
years.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>'s plan appears to be bad news for holders of
about <MONEY>$1.7 billion</MONEY> (face amount) of municipal bonds that are,
through a complicated structure, backed by guaranteed
investment contracts issued by Executive Life. These
contracts -- which aren't technically insurance -- are deemed
to be secondary and the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> department said they are
expected to have a restructured value of about <PERCENT>30%</PERCENT> of the
value of "higher priority assets," which could mean a value
of less than <MONEY>30 cents</MONEY> on the dollar.
   <PERSON>Albert M. Schlueter</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>St. Louis</LOCATION> attorney for a group of
institutions that bought GIC-backed bonds, expressed surprise
at the <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> plan. "There isn't any reason the GICs
should be treated any differently from an insurance contract
or an annuity," he said. GICs "wouldn't be marketable if a
purchaser knows he is immediately in an inferior position."
   Most other policies and annuities will be considered to
have equal priority in the restructuring process, the
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance department said, including guaranteed
investment contracts issued to various pension funds around
the country.
</TEXT>
