<LP>
   CHICAGO -- An investor in insurance products issued by
First Capital Life Insurance Co. sued Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc. in state court here, alleging that the
brokerage concern misrepresented the risks associated with
First Capital products.
   New York-based Shearson, a unit of American Express Co.,
holds a 28% stake in Los Angeles-based First Capital Life.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Capital's substantial junk-bond holdings have lost
much of their value. Regulators who seized the company in <DATE>May</DATE>
have halted policy redemptions to try to keep the company
from having to sell assets at depressed prices.
   Shearson took a <MONEY>$141 million</MONEY> charge to write off its <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital</ORGANIZATION> stake after <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators seized the concern.
   <PERSON>Bernard Giermak</PERSON>, who says he paid <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> in <DATE>1988</DATE> for a
single-premium deferred annuity issued by <ORGANIZATION>First Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>,
filed the suit in <ORGANIZATION>Cook County Circuit Court</ORGANIZATION>. The complaint
seeks class-action status on behalf of all buyers of
financial products issued by <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> that were marketed
by <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>.
   The complaint alleges that, even though <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> knew that
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> held a significant portion of "high-yield and
risky junk bonds," its agents wrongfully "made
representations to the public that <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s products
were safe investments." It also contends that <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> failed
to instruct agents to disclose "the material fact that
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION> had a substantial ownership interest in First
Capital." The suit seeks unspecified damages.
   Shearson officials couldn't be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
