<LEADPARA>  In a surprise move that jeopardizes life insurance and annuity payments to
thousands of individuals, the Internal Revenue Service has demanded $643
million in back taxes from Executive Life Insurance Co. of California,
insurance regulators said Monday.;    State Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi said he would fight the IRS claim with every legal means available,
but if the IRS succeeds, it would force liquidation of the company's $10
billion in assets. That could spell financial ruin for hundreds of thousands
of holders of insurance policies and annuities, he said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IRS DEMANDS $643 MILLION FROM EXEC LIFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Cris Oppenheimer-Pitthan contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "This would wipe out whatever capital the company has," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said. "If
this company is liquidated, the pain will be enormous for policyholders,
annuitants and the whole life insurance industry.";    In a bit of good news,
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said the insurance department received court permission <DATE>Monday</DATE> to
resume payments on death benefits and annuities.;    The court order issued
<DATE>Monday</DATE> by the <ORGANIZATION>Los Angeles Superior Court</ORGANIZATION> allows Executive First -- under the
state's conservatorship -- to resume paying <PERCENT>100 percent</PERCENT> of death benefits and
<PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> of retirement annuities to beneficiaries and policyholders. Annuity
holders, except those under guaranteed investment contracts, would receive
their current payments.;    If the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> is successful in forcing its claims,
however, all payments may stop, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;    Executive Life, the
primary operating subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, was
seized by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators on <DATE>April 11</DATE> after defaults in its huge
portfolio of high-yield "junk bonds" left it in financially hazardous
condition and sent customers rushing to cash in policies.;    Last week,
regulators in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> seized the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> subsidiary for the same reasons.;  
 The actions amounted to the largest failure yet of an insurance company.;   
Californians hold about 34,000 Executive Life insurance policies with a face
value of <MONEY>$9.5 billion</MONEY> and 16,500 annuities valued at <MONEY>$725 million</MONEY>. Overall,
Executive has 170,000 life insurance policies worth <MONEY>$38 billion</MONEY> and 75,000
annuity contracts worth <MONEY>$2.5 billion</MONEY> in force in 46 states.;     Claims by the
<ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION> would take precedence over claims of policyholders
and all other creditors of the company, industry experts said.;    If the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>
is successful in laying claim to the bulk of Executive Life's cash, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>
said policyholders would need to look to state guarantee funds to pay their
claims. Each guarantee fund has separate limits on coverage.;    <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s
fund covers up to <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the policy amount to a maximum of <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> on
annuities and <MONEY>$250,000</MONEY> on death benefits. Less traditional products, such as
guaranteed investment contracts, are not covered at all.;    Moreover,
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> noted that a previously announced rehabilitation plan, which
anticipated that the French company <ORGANIZATION>Altus Financial</ORGANIZATION> would buy Executive Life,
is also now in question because of the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> claim.;    "Altus' proposal, and
the proposals we have received from other companies, do not include anything
for this tax liability," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;    <ORGANIZATION>The IRS</ORGANIZATION> claim is based on audits
of Executive Life's <DATE>1981</DATE>, <DATE>1982</DATE> and <DATE>1983</DATE> tax years, according to regulators.
Although state <ORGANIZATION>Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION> officials knew that the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> was reviewing
Executive Life's books regarding these years, until late last <DATE>Friday</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>
had refused to disclose the scope of their claim.;    But in a letter faxed
<DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME> to Executive Life, the federal agency said it is owed <MONEY>$643.4
million</MONEY> -- or roughly <MONEY>$249 million</MONEY> in taxes and <MONEY>$394 million</MONEY> in interest and
penalties. And it wants to be paid immediately.;    "It was not a coincidence
that the state takeover and our filing a lien on the insurer came within a few
days of each other," said <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Jan Gribbon</PERSON>. "The law says that in
this kind of situation, a conservatorship, we must take action before the
assets are depleted."  </TEXT>
