ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<NS>
BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)
ACQUISITIONS &amp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
FRANCE (FR)
NEW YORK (NY)
</RE>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- First Executive Corp., whose two main
insurance subsidiaries were seized by regulators last month,
filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal Bankruptcy Code.
   The insurance holding company's bankruptcy petition had
been widely expected since insurance departments in
California and New York took control respectively of
Executive Life Insurance Co. and Executive Life of New York.
In a bit of a surprise, the parent is seeking to reorganize
rather than liquidate.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Insurance Commissioner <PERSON>John
Garamendi</PERSON> disclosed plans to auction Executive Life
Insurance, adding that a group headed by <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION> -- a
<PERCENT>60%</PERCENT>-owned subsidiary of the French bank Credit Lyonnais --
has committed to provide as much as <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> to rebuild the
company. Altus has been talked about for some time as a
prospective buyer of Executive Life's business.
   First Executive disclosed its bankruptcy petition in a
one-paragraph statement issued <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> after the filing
in federal bankruptcy court here. Chief Financial Officer
<PERSON>William L. Sanders</PERSON>, who signed the petition, said company
attorneys had advised him not to elaborate.
   In its heyday in the mid-1980s, <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Fred
Carr</PERSON>, the company's chairman, were a key part of <PERSON>Michael
Milken</PERSON>'s junk-bond network. When the junk market foundered,
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s foundations began to crumble.
   Spokesmen for the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> insurance
departments said the bankruptcy petition wouldn't affect the
more than 400,000 Americans who put substantial assets -- in
some cases their life savings -- into the two insurance
companies now under regulators' control.
   Death benefits, annuity payments and other claims continue
to be paid without interruption by the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> subsidiary,
said <PERSON>Kevin Foley</PERSON>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s deputy superintendent. In
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, after a temporary halt last month, payments have
resumed to Executive Life policyholders. The <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
insurer is paying <PERCENT>100%</PERCENT> of all death and health claims and <PERCENT>70%</PERCENT>
of annuity payments, said a spokesman.
   According to the filing, <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> has liabilities
of about <MONEY>$280 million</MONEY>, not including contingent or
unliquidated claims. The figure for total assets, <MONEY>$804
million</MONEY>, is an almost meaningless number because
substantially all of the parent's assets are its investments
in various subsidiaries, including the two seized units.
   Most of the debt is owed to foreign banks, including
<ORGANIZATION>Yasuda Trust &amp; Banking Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the filing shows. First Executive
has several series of preferred shares and more than 6,000
holders of its 85.3 million common shares. In recent months,
the common shares have traded over the counter for a few
pennies apiece.
   The filing doesn't cover any of about 30 <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>
subsidiaries. "There are still some smaller insurance
subsidiaries that appear to be relatively healthy and have
significantly more value as going concerns than they would if
they were liquidated," said <PERSON>Bruce Spector</PERSON>, an attorney at
<ORGANIZATION>Stutman, Treister &amp; Glatt</ORGANIZATION>, lead bankruptcy counsel.
   The contingent claims mentioned in the filing refer mainly
to annuities issued by Executive Life and possibly other
parent company units in connection with so-called structured
settlements, said a person close to <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>. Many of
those settlements were guaranteed by the parent company.
   Structured settlements enable accident and other victims
to receive compensation payments over time rather than in a
lump sum. First Executive's role as a guarantor was part of
intricate tax-driven arrangements that allow defendants to
remove themselves from liability for all future payments.
   <ORGANIZATION>California Insurance Commissioner Garamendi</ORGANIZATION>'s plan seems
designed to put pressure on would-be bidders for the remains
of the failed company. The auction process calls for
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators to continue negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION>Altus
Finance</ORGANIZATION> group while at the same time opening up internal
information on Executive Life to other qualified bidders. <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> said in an interview that there are three other
groups whom he said "have expressed interest, appear to meet
the qualifications, and want to get into the process."
   He said the auction process won't necessarily apply to
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s smaller <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION> unit. While inclusion of the unit will be discussed, it
"may or may not be included in any deal," he said.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION> group includes
several other French concerns, including the giant insurer
<ORGANIZATION>Cie. de Navigation Mixte</ORGANIZATION>, and several lesser-known financial
concerns, <ORGANIZATION>Euris S.A.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Eurofinac S.A.</ORGANIZATION>, and Cie. Financier
<PERSON>Alain Mallart</PERSON>.
   Would-be rescuers will likely suggest that a new company
be built from Executive Life's assets and liabilities. In
almost any case, it's expected that policyholders and other
claimants of the company will have to give up <MONEY>hundreds of
millions of dollars</MONEY> -- perhaps more -- in future payouts,
mostly through lower interest rates that would be applied to
policies. This so-called restructuring of liabilities would
likely be accompanied by a removal of some of Executive
Life's junk bonds and perhaps guarantee of others.
   ---
   <PERSON>Frederick Rose</PERSON> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
