<LP>
   California insurance regulators reached a long-awaited
pact with French investors to acquire and rehabilitate failed
Executive Life Insurance Co. The proposal, which faces many
hurdles, would entail losses of billions of dollars for
Executive Life claimants.
   The elaborate, $3 billion plan for the second-largest
insurance failure in U.S. history is intended to provide
policyholders initially with about 81 cents on the dollar. It
calls for the sale of much of Executive Life's junk bond
portfolio at a price of $2.7 billion, or a little over half
the bonds' book value.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The rehabilitation calls for Executive Life's business to
continue through a successor company, owned by seven French
firms, while a separate French investor would take over its
junk bonds.
   Before proceeding, the plan must be approved by a
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> state court after an open bidding period allows
rival offers that could improve on the French proposal. Tax
concerns as well as economic and market downturns could end
the pact. Moreover, a major group of Executive Life claimants
-- owed about <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> -- would receive nothing under the
plan.
   In announcing the agreement, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Insurance
Commissioner <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>, who took office earlier this
year, charged that state regulators "had failed to exercise
proper regulatory oversight as Executive Life slid in
financial chaos in the late <DATE>1980s</DATE>." <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said that
the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> department is cooperating with a <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Justice
Department</ORGANIZATION> investigation. He declined to elaborate.
   Executive Life, the larger of two major insurance units of
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, was deemed to be in hazardous
financial condition and seized by regulators <DATE>April 11</DATE>. The
proposed rehabilitation of the <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> insurer doesn't
directly affect efforts to sell the <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance
Co.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> unit, which is under the control of
regulators in that state.
   Despite its prospective pitfalls, the agreement announced
yesterday was welcomed by some policy holders and annuitants.
An organization representing many of them said through a
spokesman that "this is the first time in four months that
policy holders will be able to sleep soundly." <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>
praised the plan as "an excellent deal for policyholders,"
but added that he hoped other investor groups would offer
higher bids.
   The investor group, led by the French insurer <ORGANIZATION>Mutuelle
Assurance Artisanale de France</ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION>MAAF</ORGANIZATION>, is to provide
<MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> in new capital to the successor company to
Executive Life, dubbed <ORGANIZATION>Newco</ORGANIZATION>.
   Also signing was <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of the French
bank <ORGANIZATION>Credit Lyonnais</ORGANIZATION>, which would pay the <MONEY>$2.7 billion</MONEY> for
Executive Life's junk bond portfolio. The bonds to be sold
have a book value of more than <MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY>, an adviser to the
<ORGANIZATION>California Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION> said. Credit Lyonnais is to
provide credit letters totaling <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> guaranteeing the
financial performance of both the <ORGANIZATION>MAAF</ORGANIZATION> investor group and
<ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION>, which has been negotiating for months with <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
regulators.
   If completed, the proposed sale would put the newly
recapitalized Executive Life in the hands of an investor
group of relatively little-known entities. In addition to
<ORGANIZATION>MAAF</ORGANIZATION>, the partners would include the French investment and
holding companies <ORGANIZATION>Pallas Ltd.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Euris S.A.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Eurofinac S.A.</ORGANIZATION>,
SDI <ORGANIZATION>Vendome</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Marceau Investissements</PERSON> and a Swiss banking
firm, <ORGANIZATION>Omnium Geneve Group</ORGANIZATION>.
   Details about the group remained uncertain. A <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
spokesman declined to disclose the ownership that each
company would hold.
   <ORGANIZATION>MAAF</ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>'s largest mutual insurers, has assets
of about <MONEY>31 billion French francs</MONEY> (<MONEY>$5.34 billion</MONEY>), relatively
small by the standards of major world insurers. Founded in
<DATE>1950</DATE> to provide auto insurance for French craftsmen, it has
shown little interest until now in investing abroad.
   In addition to "<ORGANIZATION>Newco</ORGANIZATION>," the successor to Executive Life,
yesterday's agreement also anticipates a "liquidating trust"
that would receive about <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> book value of real
estate assets that won't move to <ORGANIZATION>Newco</ORGANIZATION> and which <ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION> won't
buy. The liquidating trust also will receive claims from
state insurance guaranty funds and any settlements from
extensive litigation that may develop. Proceeds from the
trust would be added to policyholder assets, and could raise
future payouts above the <MONEY>81 cents</MONEY> on the dollar anticipated
at the start of the rehabilitation.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said details of the agreement are expected
to be filed in about 20 days with a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> state court
that currently is overseeing Executive Life's
conservatorship. After the court filing, there is to be a
60-day period for competitive bidding by other interested
groups.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said that "there is at least one other
bidder" actively interested in a transaction, and that there
"may be" two or three others interested. He declined to name
any of the prospective bidders.
   The announcement contained bad news for holders of about
<MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> of municipal bonds backed by Executive Life
guaranteed investment contracts, for which the agreement
makes no provision whatsoever. Earlier, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>
proposed a settlement of <MONEY>30 cents</MONEY> on the dollar with
bondholders. But negotiations have broken down and
bondholders have asked a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> court to determine
whether the guaranteed investment contracts that back the
bonds are a form of insurance policy that would rank equally
with more conventional life and annuity contracts.
   <PERSON>Christine Franklin</PERSON>, an attorney for one of the
municipalities issuing the bonds, expressed regret at the
decision but said the issuers, bondholders, and their
trustees will pursue their claims under a legal action
scheduled for trial <DATE>Sept. 30</DATE>.
   Court orders related to municipal bond claims could delay
or even derail the rehabilitation plan, lawyers noted.
   Other impediments threaten the prospective pact, <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> noted. Among them is an <ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION>
claim for <MONEY>$643 million</MONEY> in back taxes and interest against
Executive Life for certain revenue in the early <DATE>1980</DATE>'s. The
tax implications of the proposed transaction itself aren't
clear and an adverse ruling from the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> on this could
scuttle the deal, the insurance commissioner said.
   The agreement permits the French investment group and
<ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION> to abandon the plan if economic conditions sour
substantially. Under certain conditions, however, <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> may retain a right to sell Executive Life's junk
bonds to <ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION> at the <MONEY>$2.7 billion</MONEY> price whether or not
Executive Life is sold to the investor group. <ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION>, under
certain conditions, could also require the sale.
   ---
   <PERSON>Charles Fleming</PERSON> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
