<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Two investors in troubled First Capital
Holdings Inc.'s insurance products sued Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc., charging that the brokerage firm underplayed
the riskiness of their investment.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court here, says Shearson
misled investors into believing that First Capital products
such as annuities were "safe, risk-free and guaranteed"
investments. It alleges that after Shearson acquired a 44%
interest in First Capital, it organized a national effort to
sell First Capital annuities and used selling techniques
"typical of securities sales" as opposed to traditional
annuity sales.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The lawsuit further charges that <ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>, which at the
time controlled a majority of seats on <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s board,
was fully aware of the insurance holding company's "risky
investment policies" and "imperiled financial status." It
noted that as much as <PERCENT>38%</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s assets were
invested in high-yield junk bonds. The lawsuit, filed by
investors <PERSON>Jay</PERSON> and <PERSON>Rae Peshkin</PERSON>, seeks class-action status.
   First Capital's junk-bond investments have deteriorated
sharply in value and regulators have halted policy
redemptions at <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s insurance businesses, citing
the risk of major losses from forcing the company to use up
its cash and to sell assets at depressed prices. <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s
insurance commissioner has called on <ORGANIZATION>American Express Co.</ORGANIZATION>,
<ORGANIZATION>Shearson</ORGANIZATION>'s parent, to take responsibility for shoring up
<ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> by whatever means necessary.
   Shearson officials denied the lawsuit's charges. "Such
allegations are without foundation and will be contested,"
said a spokesman, who noted that the company has reduced its
interest in <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> to <PERCENT>28%</PERCENT>. He also said a "handful" of
other similar cases are pending against the company.
</TEXT>
