<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; INSURANCE; RANKING; SURVEY; RESULT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Executive Life Insurance Co. led California's big life insurers in consumer
complaints in the year before its seizure by state regulators, according to a
survey released Wednesday.;    Overall, United Insurance of America, the 47th
largest company in the state, had the most complaints of the 50 life insurance
companies surveyed by the state Insurance Department.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SURVEY RATES INSURERS OF LIFE, HEALTH
RANKINGS BASED ON COMPLAINTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  California News  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     <ORGANIZATION>Transamerica Occidental Life</ORGANIZATION> had the fewest complaints of the top five life
insurance firms in <DATE>1990.</DATE>;    Among the five largest health insurers in the
state, <ORGANIZATION>Aetna Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> had the most complaints settled against it
last year. <ORGANIZATION>Healthnet</ORGANIZATION> had the fewest.;    Insurance Commissioner <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON>
said he hoped the "test scores," would help consumers shop for the best deal
and encourage companies with the most complaints to "clean up their act.";   
He released the report a day after issuing a similar survey of auto and
homeowner insurers.;    "For those who failed their exams, they better shape
up, because there's going to be another exam next year," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> told a
Capitol news conference.;    Survey is one test;  However, he cautioned that
consumers shouldn't judge companies solely on the survey but should also
consider firms' financial stability and policy prices.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> called
<ORGANIZATION>United Insurance</ORGANIZATION> the "really bad news company in life insurance" with nine
times as many complaints as the industry average. A corporate executive, who
asked that his name be withheld, said he couldn't comment until he read the
survey.;    Five life insurers had zero complaints settled against them in
<DATE>1990</DATE>. They were <ORGANIZATION>Security Life of Denver</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Standard Insurance</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Aid Association</ORGANIZATION>
for Lutherans, <ORGANIZATION>Phoenix Mutual Life</ORGANIZATION> and Crown LIfe.;    Complaint leader; 
Among health insurers, <ORGANIZATION>Pioneer Life of Illinois</ORGANIZATION>, the 44th largest in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, led overall in complaints with 15 times the industry average,
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said. Company officials had no immediate comment.;    <ORGANIZATION>Group Life
Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the 31st biggest health insurance firm, had zero complaints.;  
 The survey ranked the companies by the number of complaints as compared with
policies written. To make the list, a complaint had to involve a violation of
insurance law or code, or come from a client who turned to the state only
after failing to get a response from an insurer.;    Two junk bond-laden
companies that were seized this <DATE>spring</DATE> by the state, Executive Life and <ORGANIZATION>First
Capital Life</ORGANIZATION>, ranked third and fourth in complaints among life insurers last
year.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said he would demand the companies to do better once they
get back on their feet.;    Executive Life, then the fourth largest in the
state, had 57 complaints, or .343 for every <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> in premiums. First
Capital, then the 46th largest, had 11 complaints, or .308 per <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> in
premiums.;    Leaders chastised;  <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> chastised <ORGANIZATION>Prudential Insurance of
America and Metropolitan Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the first and third largest life
insurers in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, respectively, for ranking the eighth and ninth worst
in the survey.;    "As industry leaders, I expect them to lead in good service
as well as in sales," he said.;    <ORGANIZATION>Prudential</ORGANIZATION> received 94 complaints, or .227
per <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> in premiums. Metropolitan 38 complaints, or .144 per <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY>
in premiums.;    Metropolitan also ranked ninth worst among health insurers,
with 49 complaints, or .413 per <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> in premiums. " 'Get Met' is their
slogan. I suggest that if they don't improve their consumer service,
Californians will simply say, 'Met, nyet,' " <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;    Insurer
disputes results;  <ORGANIZATION>MetLife</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Charles Sahner</PERSON> said he believes the
survey results for the company were artificially high. "Less than one-third of
<PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT> of the millions of claims we pay each year result in a complaint,"
<PERSON>Sahner</PERSON> said in a statement released from the company's <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> headquarters.;
   Last year, the <ORGANIZATION>Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION> investigated 1,197 complaints about
life insurance companies and 2,804 complaints involving health insurers,
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said. As a result, the agency recovered more than <MONEY>$5 million</MONEY> for
life insurance policyholders and <MONEY>$6.5 million</MONEY> from health insurance customers,
he said.  </TEXT>
