<LEADPARA>  State insurance officials met on Wednesday with two top executives of troubled
First Capital Life Insurance Co. who have been accused of cashing personal
policies while thousands of customers were frozen out.;    The officials met
in San Francisco with First Capital President Fred Buck and Julia S. Kelly,
senior vice president for administration, according to Elena Stern,
spokeswoman for the state Department of Insurance.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  INSURANCE EXECS ACCUSED OF CASHING POLICIES
WHILE CUSTOMERS COULDN'T  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Stern provided few details of the meeting but said the probe was part of an
ongoing investigation into operations of the San Diego-based insurer. She said
there is no criminal investigation so far.;    State Insurance Commissioner
<PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON> ordered <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s funds frozen on <DATE>May 10</DATE>. Four days later
he seized the company and placed it under department conservatorship.;   
Thousands of <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> policyholders tried to recover more than <MONEY>$265
million</MONEY> in assets in <DATE>April</DATE> and early <DATE>May</DATE>, following reports of its heavy
investment in junk bonds.;    But the insurer told them their requests would
take 30 days rather than the usual two weeks.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>'s <DATE>May 10</DATE> order
prohibited policyholders from cashing out their policies and allowed the
company to honor only life insurance death benefits and payments for
annuities.;    Investigators are trying to determine whether Buck and <PERSON>Kelly</PERSON>
violated their positions of trust by using access and inside information to
unfair advantage over the company's other policyholders.;    <ORGANIZATION>The San Diego
Tribune</ORGANIZATION> reported on the investigation Wednesday.;    <PERSON>Charlie Perkins</PERSON>, a
spokesman for the company in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>
executives have been meeting regularly with state insurance officials since
the state seized the insurer.;    <PERSON>Perkins</PERSON> said he did not know the topic of
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>'s meeting and declined to comment further.;    <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> has
<MONEY>$4.5 billion</MONEY> in assets and 260,000 policyholders.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> has told the
<ORGANIZATION>Tribune</ORGANIZATION> his department is auditing <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION>'s books and is investigating
whether any <ORGANIZATION>First Capital</ORGANIZATION> executives cashed their personal policies before the
state seizure.  </TEXT>
