<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The California Insurance Department said
two top officers of a now-failed First Capital Holdings Corp.
insurance unit reversed efforts to take money out of the unit
that were started shortly before the unit was seized by state
regulators.
   As previously reported, the California department
investigated whether Fred A. Buck, president of First Capital
Life Insurance Co., and Julia S. Kelly, a senior vice
president, improperly put themselves ahead of other
policyholders with attempted withdrawals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The insurance department spokesman said that <PERSON>Mr. Buck</PERSON>
redeposited <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> taken as a loan against an insurance
policy and that <PERSON>Ms. Kelly</PERSON> had canceled plans to transfer a
<MONEY>$40,000</MONEY> annuity to another insurance company.
   The spokesman said that <PERSON>Mr. Buck</PERSON>'s and <PERSON>Ms. Kelly</PERSON>'s actions
were voluntary and their earlier plans weren't illegal. The
department investigation was initiated, the spokesman said,
because the transactions were undertaken about three days
before <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators moved to assert control over the
company's assets, raising concerns that department
confidentiality had been breached.
   Neither <PERSON>Mr. Buck</PERSON> nor <PERSON>Ms. Kelly</PERSON> was available to comment.
The executives previously have declined to comment on the
matter.
   Other matters concerning the company and employee actions
before the <DATE>May 13</DATE> state seizure are being investigated, the
insurance department spokesman said. The seizure has resulted
in a moratorium on all policy loans, redemptions and
transfers.
</TEXT>
