<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Internal Revenue Service demanded $643
million in back taxes and penalties from First Executive
Corp.'s largest insurance unit, threatening efforts to
resuscitate the failed unit and endangering payments to
policyholders.
   The claim, filed Friday by the IRS, was disclosed
yesterday by John Garamendi, California's insurance
commissioner, who on April 11 put the unit, Executive Life
Insurance Co., under regulatory control, saying that it was
in "hazardous" financial condition. It is the largest
insurance failure ever.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> obtained a court order
authorizing Executive Life to pay <PERCENT>100%</PERCENT> of death benefits and
<PERCENT>70%</PERCENT> of qualified retirement annuities. Such payments have
been halted since the company was put under regulatory
control. Orders barring policy redemptions and loans remain
in effect. So too do prohibitions on payments under most
so-called Guaranteed Income Contracts, unless they apply to
specific annuitants named in the contracts, a spokesman for
the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance department said.
   It's expected that life insurance payments under the new
authorization will total about <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY> over the next 12
months and that annual annuity payments will total <MONEY>$174
million</MONEY>.
   Although <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> claims of some sort are relatively common
step in bankruptcies and insurance insolvencies, the size of
the claim -- which might or might not be upheld -- is nearly
half again the <MONEY>$474.1 million</MONEY> surplus and capital reported by
Executive Life for the <DATE>1990 year end</DATE>. <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators
told the company before taking it over that they were
considering accounting revisions that would result in a major
change to even the reported number.
   It wasn't clear how quickly the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> might move with its
demands on Executive Life. A demand for immediate funds could
result in an immediate move to liquidation, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>
said. The notice sent to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s insurance department
demands immediate payment, but the agency said it won't take
any action until it receives approval from a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> state
court. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said he won't authorize any payments
unless ordered by the court.
   The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> liens, filed with the <ORGANIZATION>California Secretary of
State</ORGANIZATION>'s office and with the state insurance department, list
<MONEY>$249 million</MONEY> sought in back taxes for the years <DATE>1981</DATE> to <DATE>1983</DATE>,
and <MONEY>$394 million</MONEY> in penalties and interest.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> cautioned that the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> claim, if upheld,
could end payments to policyholders and annuitants and force
the company into liquidation, a step that the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
commissioner and other regulators have sought to avoid. <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> charged the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> with a last-minute action, saying
"these assets are desperately needed to pay Executive Life
policyholders and annuitants."
   In <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, a spokesman for the state's department of
insurance said the <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s second-largest unit,
<ORGANIZATION>Executive Life Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, hasn't been served
with any claims for back taxes. The <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> unit, seized
last week by state insurance regulators, has continued to pay
death benefits and annuity payments, unlike <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, which
halted them while regulators analyzed the financial state of
the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> company.
   People close to <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION>, the <PERCENT>65%</PERCENT>-owned subsidiary of
Credit Lyonnais that has been discussing with regulators the
possible purchase and restructuring of both Executive Life
units, said that <ORGANIZATION>Altus</ORGANIZATION> remains interested in a transaction
but is analyzing the prospective impact of the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> action.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> claim stems from a <DATE>1989</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>U.S.
Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> decision affecting taxation of insurance
companies. The decision, concerning <ORGANIZATION>Colonial American Life
Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, limited the way insurance companies can deduct
certain costs of reinsurance. The court held that costs for
reinsurance -- which passes risks from one insurance company
to another -- must be deducted over time from taxable income,
rather than be deducted in the year that they're incurred.
   Insurance companies were allowed to make certain
adjustments in their <DATE>1989</DATE> filing that would limit their
liability for back taxes under the ruling. However, if those
adjustments weren't made, then all amounts owing for prior
years under the court-established principle can be levied, an
<ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> official said.
   It's not clear whether Executive Life made the required
adjustments for <DATE>1989</DATE>. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said people in his
department were aware of an <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> audit but that the federal
agency had declined to disclose details of its investigation,
which also wasn't included in a long list of government
investigations of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> and its units disclosed in
the company's 10K annual filing with the <ORGANIZATION>Securities and
Exchange Commission</ORGANIZATION>.
   Stressing the "enormous" potential damage of a liquidation
on Executive Life policyholders, the insurance industry and
state insurance guaranty funds, <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said he was
contacting people in the <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> administration and in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>
in an effort to have the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> action reversed. He added that
the current assessment is only for the years <DATE>1981</DATE> to <DATE>1983</DATE> and
that the application of the same tax principle to later years
could impose a much larger cost.
   The <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance commissioner said he will
"re-evaluate" in 90 days the latest plan to pay benefits if
the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> tax charge hasn't been eliminated. He labeled the
chance of selling or restructuring the <ORGANIZATION>California Executive
Life</ORGANIZATION> unit as "slim to none" if the tax liability remains.
   <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> said that, in addition to <ORGANIZATION>Altus Finance</ORGANIZATION>, two
other groups have expressed interest in a purchase of
Executive Life. He declined to identify the groups, adding
that they hadn't formally made an offer. He indicated that
his department is considering at least an informal auction
process for Executive Life, agreeing to distribute detailed
information to interested buyers.
</TEXT>
