<LP>
   New Jersey Life Insurance Co., already fighting off
seizure attempts by New Jersey regulators, was ordered by
California to stop writing and renewing policies.
   The California order comes as New Jersey seeks in court
today to take over New Jersey Life, which the state says is
insolvent and requires state intervention. The state won a
restraining order against the insurance company May 20, after
state examiners found what they believed to be a $36 million
deficit for New Jersey Life at the end of 1990. The state
said the company had claimed a $10 million surplus.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The restraining order expired at the end of <DATE>May</DATE>. A hearing
is scheduled today in state court in <LOCATION>Hackensack</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, to
determine whether the company should be seized by the state.
<ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Paramus</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, is challenging a
state takeover.
   According to the order issued by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Insurance
Commissioner <PERSON>John Garamendi</PERSON> against <ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION>, which
does <PERCENT>16%</PERCENT> of its business in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, the company's
financial condition threatened to "render it insolvent" or
force it into liquidation. The stability of life insurance
contracts for 4,723 Californians was threatened, <PERSON>Mr.
Garamendi</PERSON> said.
   The <DATE>1990</DATE> annual statement filed by <ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION> with
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance regulators indicated a reserve credit of
<MONEY>$25.2 million</MONEY> for reinsurance ceded to <ORGANIZATION>RepublicVanguard Life
Insurance Co.</ORGANIZATION> under a "split co-insurance/modified
co-insurance" treaty. <PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON> recently said that such
treaties wouldn't be accepted in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> because they
artificially inflate an insurer's capital levels.
   As a result, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> said, <ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION> actually had
a <MONEY>$15.2 million</MONEY> deficit, putting the company below the
minimum capital and surplus needed to do business in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. A hearing is scheduled for <DATE>Aug. 16</DATE> in <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> to determine whether the state will take further
action.
   <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s actions didn't surprise <ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION>. "It
is not unexpected that several states would follow the
actions of <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>," said <PERSON>Richard Smith</PERSON>, a company
spokesman. Regarding the <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION> court hearing, <PERSON>Mr. Smith</PERSON>
said, "We are not insolvent, and we are continuing to service
our policyholders, and the company is looking for an
opportunity to present the facts as we see them."
   As of <DATE>Dec. 31, 1990</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>New Jersey Life</ORGANIZATION> had a total of <MONEY>$3.24
billion</MONEY> of insurance in force, of which <MONEY>$902 million</MONEY> was in
<LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>. It currently has assets of <MONEY>$161 million</MONEY>.
</TEXT>
