<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; COURT; INSURANCE; COMPANY; STOCK; FRAUD; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  California regulators went to court today to seize Executive Life Insurance
Co., whose parent company was Michael Milken's top junk-bond customer and
suffered huge losses when the market for those bonds dissolved.;    "I have
found Executive Life to be in a hazardous condition, and today I'm seeking a
court-supervised conservatorship of the company," said state Insurance
Commissioner John Garamendi.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STATE SEEKS TO SEIZE LIFE INSURANCE FIRM  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Ken McLaughlin contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     He cited Executive Life's large junk-bond portfolio and insufficient
reserve capital. Of Executive Life's <MONEY>$10.1 billion</MONEY> in assets, about <MONEY>$6.4
billion</MONEY> is invested in high-risk, high-yield junk bonds, he said.;   
<PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Superior Court</ORGANIZATION> action was necessary to protect thousands of
people who have invested in the company.;    "These are the people who are
counting on this money -- and deservedly -- to enjoy and protect them for the
rest of their lives," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said.;    He added that Executive Life was
"fully cooperating in the transition.";    <PERSON>Bill Schulz</PERSON>, a spokesman for the
state <ORGANIZATION>Department of Insurance</ORGANIZATION>, said Executive Life would become "the largest
life insurance company ever to be placed under conservatorship" in the
country.;    Executive Life has 170,000 life insurance policies with a face
value of <MONEY>$38 billion</MONEY>, <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said. Its parent, <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, is a
<MONEY>$15 billion</MONEY> holding company which also operates Executive Life of <LOCATION>New York.</LOCATION>;  
 <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> attracted customers during the booming '80s with low rates
made possible by high returns on junk bonds. First Executive's chairman, <PERSON>Fred
Carr</PERSON>, was the top customer of <PERSON>Michael Milken</PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION>Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.</ORGANIZATION> official who built an empire on junk bonds.;    Then the junk
bond market collapsed. Since the start of <DATE>1989</DATE>, a quarter of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION>'s
junk bond portfolio has defaulted. As of last month, its <MONEY>$9 billion</MONEY> junk-bond
portfolio carried a market value of <MONEY>$6.7 billion.</MONEY>;    Earlier this month,
<ORGANIZATION>First Executive</ORGANIZATION> reported a loss of <MONEY>$465.9 million</MONEY> for the <DATE>fourth quarter</DATE> and
said <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators had shut off the cash flow from its troubled
insurance units.;    Last week, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> regulators ordered <ORGANIZATION>Executive Life of
New York</ORGANIZATION> to stop writing new policies in the 23 states where it is licensed
and to immediately add <MONEY>$125 million</MONEY> to its reserves.;    <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
regulators, fearing for Executive Life's solvency, barred the company from
making interest payments to the parent firm.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said he expects <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION> regulators at some point will seize Executive Life of <LOCATION>New York.</LOCATION>;    <PERSON>Kevin
Foley</PERSON>, deputy superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION>New York State Insurance Department</ORGANIZATION>, said
his agency hasn't "made the final determination yet" about Executive Life's
solvency.;    The <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> regulators are finishing an actuarial examination
of Executive Life and will "have a definitive statement" next week on the
insurer's condition, he said.  </TEXT>
