<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- An issue central to one of the nation's
largest insurance failures will be debated in a trial opening
today, as trustees and underwriters of $1.85 billion in
municipal bonds backed by Executive Life Insurance Co. seek a
ruling that the bond claims rank equally with insurance
policies issued by the failed company.
   The case, in state court in Los Angeles, will determine
the fate of assets in the insolvency and uphold or overturn
California Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi's position
that Executive Life's obligation to the bondholders ranks
junior to its traditional insurance contracts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A victory by the bond claimants would sharply reduce
recoveries for large insurance policies and pose greater
demands on state insurance guaranty funds, as limited assets
would be used to cover a further <MONEY>$1.85 billion</MONEY> in liabilities
that barely enter into current workout proposals. Los
Angeles-based Executive Life is the one-time principal
insurance unit of <ORGANIZATION>First Executive Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which itself is now
in Chapter 11 bankruptcy law proceedings.
   Analysts say that a bondholders' victory also could more
than double the value of the bonds themselves. The securities
currently trade for as little as <MONEY>20 cents</MONEY> on the dollar and
stand to recover almost nothing under the insurance
commissioners' current plan.
   The so-called "muni-GICs" have been the focus of a bitter
debate for months, with assertions of bad faith from both
sides in the scramble to cover about <MONEY>$9.87 billion</MONEY> in
liabilities with assets estimated to be worth roughly <MONEY>$3
billion</MONEY> less.
   <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> regulators contend that the bond litigation is
a selfish attack on scarce assets by the bond trustees and
securities underwriters, who face claims from bondholders in
separate litigation. "These people are trying to take money
that is in trust for {Executive Life's} policyholders and
bail themselves out of liabilities to bondholders," asserts
<PERSON>Karl Rubinstein</PERSON>, special counsel to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s insurance
commissioner, adding that "their position would be
devastating to policyholders around the country."
   For their part, bond advocates argue that the position of
<PERSON>Mr. Garamendi</PERSON>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s first elected insurance
commissioner, is colored by political bias and ambition,
noting that most bond holders neither live nor vote in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, while many major insurance policyholders do. "We
see this as a political opinion," says <PERSON>Julio Herrera</PERSON>, an
analyst at <ORGANIZATION>RRH Capital Management</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, investment
advisers with clients who have invested in the bonds.
   Central to the case is whether the so-called "funding
agreements" governing money from the bonds are a part of
Executive Life's conventional insurance business or a
miscellaneous claim against the company's assets.
   Lawyers for the bond underwriters assert that the funding
agreements are in principal the same as various
company-issued annuities. If the court is to set aside the
muni-GICs, these lawyers argue, then it must set aside nearly
<MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY> of other claims, including annuities bought by
corporate pension funds and used to provide for victims in
personal injury cases.
   Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION>Texas Commerce Bank-El Paso</ORGANIZATION>, a unit of
<ORGANIZATION>Chemical Banking Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, and trustees for one bond
issue, take a somewhat different tack. They argue that
bondholder claims aren't governed by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> law but by
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> law, where the funding agreements recently were deemed
a conventional insurance product.
   <PERSON>Mr. Rubinstein</PERSON>, special counsel to the commissioner,
retorts that the assertion of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> law "is a product of the
Looney Toons studio in Hollywood."
   The tale of the muni-GICs began with the sale in <DATE>1986</DATE> of
just seven issues of the unorthodox bonds by municipal
agencies in <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nebraska</LOCATION>, and
<LOCATION>Colorado</LOCATION>. There were multiple issues in <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
Although technically intended as borrowings by the municipal
agencies for government purposes, the monies went directly
into funding agreements at Executive Life, where they could
be withdrawn by the municipalities only under the most
onerous terms. According to court documents, just <MONEY>$6 million</MONEY>
of the <MONEY>$1.85 billion</MONEY> in muni-GICs was ever drawn for
government purposes. Executive Life, in turn, invested much
of the money in junk bonds. <ORGANIZATION>Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, the
failed investment banking concern and former employer of
now-jailed junk-bond king <PERSON>Michael Milken</PERSON>, played a pivotal
role in all but one of the bond issues.
   <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> insurance regulators contend that the bonds
were in effect an illegitimate ruse that converted Triple-A
bond borrowings into fodder for the burgeoning junk-bond
market. "The underlying transactions are a scandal of
unprecedented proportions," says the state's insurance
department in a brief to the court. State officials argue
that the bondholders' proper route for recovery is through
the extensive civil fraud actions now consolidated in federal
court in <LOCATION>New Orleans</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
